---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const title = "EKS pricing: what to include in a realistic cost estimate";
const description =
  "A practical EKS pricing checklist: nodes, control plane, load balancers, storage, logs/metrics, and data transfer - with calculators to estimate each part.";
const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is the biggest EKS cost driver?",
    a: "Usually node compute. But for many real clusters, logs/metrics, load balancers, NAT gateways, and cross-AZ traffic can be significant.",
  },
  {
    q: "Why do EKS estimates miss?",
    a: "They model only nodes. A realistic estimate includes control plane fees, storage, networking transfer, and observability.",
  },
  {
    q: "How should I size nodes for budgeting?",
    a: "Start from pod requests, add overhead/headroom, then convert to node count. Validate against a representative week of metrics once you have them.",
  },
  {
    q: "What should I validate after deploying?",
    a: "Check: node-hours, load balancer count, NAT GB processed, cross-AZ transfer, and log ingestion GB/day. These are common surprises.",
  },
];
---
<GuideLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/guides/aws-eks-pricing"
  lastUpdated="2026-01-22"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <p>
    The easiest way to underestimate EKS cost is to model only nodes. Node compute is usually the biggest part, but a
    realistic budget includes several surrounding line items.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 1: Baseline node cost</h2>
  <p>
    Start by sizing nodes from workload requests, then apply a blended $/hour. Tools:
    <a href="/calculators/kubernetes-requests-limits-calculator/">Requests &amp; limits</a> and{" "}
    <a href="/calculators/kubernetes-node-cost-calculator/">node cost</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 2: Include the common add-ons</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Control plane fee</strong>: fixed hourly fee in many managed Kubernetes offerings.</li>
    <li><strong>Load balancers / gateways</strong>: can be significant for high-traffic services.</li>
    <li><strong>Storage</strong>: PVs, snapshots, and object storage buckets.</li>
    <li><strong>Logs and metrics</strong>: often the biggest surprise cost.</li>
    <li><strong>Data transfer</strong>: cross-zone/region traffic and internet egress.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Validation checklist</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Control plane: cluster count x $/hour x 730.</li>
    <li>Networking: check NAT gateway GB processed and cross-AZ transfer.</li>
    <li>Observability: check log ingestion GB/day and metrics cardinality growth.</li>
    <li>Load balancers: count of always-on load balancers and capacity-unit drivers.</li>
  </ul>

